3–Overleden","1235–1290":"1235–1290","1171–1250":"1171–1250","1171–Female":"1171–Overleden","1190":"1190","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1171":"1171","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","about 1228":"circa 1228","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","Abt 1233":"circa 1233","1233":"1233","about 1235":"circa 1235","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","Coton, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1195–":"1195–Deceased","1195–Male":"1195–Deceased","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1233–Male":"1233–Deceased","1235–1290":"1235–1290","1171–1250":"1171–1250","1171–Female":"1171–Deceased","1190":"1190","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1171":"1171","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","about 1228":"about 1228","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","Abt 1233":"about 1233","1233":"1233","about 1235":"about 1235","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","Coton, Shropshire, England":"Coton, Shropshire, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cotton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called from Old English <i>(æt) cotum</i> (dative plural of <i>cot</i>) ‘at the cottages or huts’ (or sometimes possibly from a Middle English plural, <i>coten</i>). Examples include Coton (Cambridgeshire, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire), Cottam (East Yorkshire, Lancashire, Nottinghamshire), and Cotham (Nottinghamshire). Particularly common in Staffordshire.","French: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Nicolas</i> (see   Nicholas  ), derived via <i>Nicot</i>, or of the personal name   Jacques  , derived via <i>Jacot</i>.","History: John Cotton (1584–1652) was a noted Puritan preacher, who landed at Boston, MA, from London in 1633 and became leader of the Congregationalists in America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cotten","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cotton  .","Altered form of German <b>Kotten</b>, a habitational name from any of several places so named in Rhineland, Westphalia, Silesia, etc., or perhaps an American shortened form of composite German surnames such as <b>Kottenhagen</b>, <b>Kottenhoff</b>, <b>Kottenkamp</b> (see   Koth  )."]},{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]},{"name":"Cotham","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottom","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottam","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): variant of   Cotton  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"FitzWilliam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name   William  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":20,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":29,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":64,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":95,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Simon FitzWilliam de Cotton was born in 1195, in Coton, Shropshire, England, his father, William de Cotentin, was 24 and his mother, Mrs. William de Cotentin, was 25. He married Enid Grosvenor de Maatenloch about 1228, in Northampton, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"1195–":"1195–Surnud","1195–Male":"1195–Surnud","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1225–Male":"1225–Su